# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ambrose-swasey
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ambrose-swasey/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen graduated from Thomas Jefferson High School in San Antonio, Texas.
[src:ambrose-swasey/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He received a Bachelor of Science degree from Texas A&M University in 1952, a Master of Science degree from Stevens Institute of Technology in 1958, and an honorary doctorate from Stevens in 1982.
[src:ambrose-swasey/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen joined NASA in 1962 and served in key leadership roles critical to the success of the flights and lunar landings of the Apollo Program.
[src:ambrose-swasey/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] From 1969 to 1972, Cohen was the manager for the Apollo Command and Service Modules.
[src:ambrose-swasey/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He oversaw the design, development, production and test flights of the Space Shuttles as manager of NASA's Space Shuttle Orbiter Project Office from 1972 to 1982.
[src:ambrose-swasey/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After serving as Director of Engineering at Johnson for several years, he was named director of the center in 1986, serving in that post until 1993.
[src:ambrose-swasey/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After his retirement from NASA, Cohen taught mechanical engineering design at Texas A&M University.
[src:ambrose-swasey/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] In 2000, he was appointed Professor Emeritus, and in 2010, he was awarded an honorary Doctor of Letters.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] Bovik received a Primetime Emmy Award in 2015 for his development of perception-based video quality measurement tools that are now standards in television production.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] Al Bovik was educated at the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign (PhD 1984).
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] He has made numerous fundamental contributions to the fields of digital photography, digital television, digital image processing, digital video processing, digital cinema, and computational visual perception.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] He is particularly well known for his work on low-level vision, natural scene modeling, image quality, and video quality.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] He has published more than 1000 technical articles, books, and patents in these areas.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] Overall, his work has been cited in the scientific and engineering literature more than 200,000 times according to Google Scholar.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] He is one of the most highly cited engineers in the world according to the Web of Science.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] Bovik is an elected member of the United States National Academy of Engineering (NAE), an elected Foreign Fellow of the Indian National Academy of Engineering (INAE), an elected Fellow of the U.S.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] National Academy of Inventors, and an elected foreign member of Academia Europaea (2023).
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] He is also a Life Fellow of the IEEE, a Fellow of Optica and of the Society of Photo-Optical and Instrumentation Engineers (SPIE), an Honorary Fellow of the Royal Photographic Society (HonFRPS) and an Honorary Member of the Society for Imaging Science and Technology (IS&T).
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] He is a voting member of the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences (Television Academy) and was named an inaugural member of its Science and Technology Peer Group.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] He was named a Distinguished Alumnus of the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign in 2008.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] His high-dynamic range (HDR) add-on model HDRMAX, which improves the quality prediction performance of leading models is marketed and used worldwide.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] He was the founder and First General Chair of the IEEE International Conference on Image Processing (ICIP).
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] He also co-founded (with David Munson, Jr.) the IEEE Transactions on Image Processing and was its longest-serving Editor-in-Chief, with a tenure of six years.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] Bovik's academic legacy includes serving as the supervising professor of more than 70 PhD graduates, more than 50 master's degree recipients, and more than two dozen post-doctoral researchers.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] His award-winning online courseware is used internationally: SIVA – Courseware for Signal, Image, Video and Audio Processing.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] This online courseware offers online curricula for digital image and video processing and digital signal processing.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] SIVA includes hundreds of signal, image and video processing demonstrations delivering live, interactive audio-visual experiences of signal and image processing algorithms.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-bovik] Bovik has received a number of major international awards.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-howard-engineer] Howard was born in Washington, D.C., in 1905.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-howard-engineer] He obtained his BSc in electrical engineering from Purdue University in 1927.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-howard-engineer] After his graduation in 1927, Howard started his lifelong career at the General Electric Company in Schenectady, New York as electrical engineer.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-howard-engineer] He advanced rapidly various positions, and moved into steam turbine activities in 1941.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-howard-engineer] In World War II at General Electric, Howard managed the development of aircraft gas turbine engine for the United States Air Force, and developed the TG 100 and TG 180 turboprop engine.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-howard-engineer] Coffin Award by General Electric for his "accomplishments in connection with the design and development of the TG100 and TG180 aircraft gas turbines." In 1954, he was awarded the honorary degree of doctor of engineering by Purdue University.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alan-howard-engineer] In 1962, he had been elected Fellow of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, and in 1964, he was awarded the ASME Medal.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was born in Morris, Illinois and graduated from Cuyahoga Falls High School, OH in 1880.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] In addition to his interest in tribology and bearings, Kingsbury enjoyed the world of arts, history, and letters.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] He devoted much time to the study of foreign languages.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury died in Greenwich, Connecticut 1943, and is buried at the Green-Wood Cemetery, Brooklyn, New York.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] In 1884, Kingsbury attended the University of Akron to study Scientific-Latin courses.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] He dropped out and worked as a machine apprentice in Cuyahoga Falls.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury credited this as an important experience that led him to advance his career in engineering.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury resumed his formal education at Ohio State University, but he again dropped out to work as a machinist with the Warner and Swasey Company in Cleveland.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received his mechanical engineering degree from Cornell University in 1887.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] It was at Cornell that he met Professor Robert Henry Thurston.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Professor Thurston was instrumental in shaping Kingsbury's interest in bearings and tribology.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Working under Professor Thurston, Kingsbury conducted tests on bearing materials for the Pennsylvania Railroad.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] His craftsmanship, honed by his experience in machine shops, allowed Kingsbury to fit half-bushings to the journal by scraping.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] His hand fitting produced the small tolerances that promoted film lubrication.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] These bearings, when ran showed no measurable signs of wear, and was Kingsbury's prompt to the creation of the thrust bearings which now bear his name.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury pursued a teaching position at the University of New Hampshire.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Within two years, he was a professor of Mechanical Engineering courses at the university.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] His new position at the university allowed him to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] During his time at the University of New Hampshire, he created an innovative test machine to measure friction in coarse pitch, lubricated screw threads at loads of up to 14,000 psi.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] The usefulness of this invention received mixed reviews from the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME).
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] His research also covered fluid lubricated bearings, and he published a paper entitled "Experiments with an Air Lubricated Bearing".
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] It was at this university that he envisioned the Kingsbury thrust bearing.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Worcester Polytechnic Institute to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] He secured expansions for laboratory facilities and funding to continue his tests on a centrally pivoted thrust bearing with the aid of his students.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury's research at the University of New Hampshire led him to conceive an early Kingsbury bearing that consisted of several stationary arc segments facing a thrust collar on the rotating shaft.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Each segment would have a boss on the side away from the thrust collar, allowing it to tilt and form an oil wedge that would carry the thrust.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tested this new bearing with a modified version of his earlier screw thread testing machine.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] The bearing was successful with pressures of up to 4,000 psi at speeds of 285 rpm.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] This pressure exceeded that for common collar-type bearings by a factor of 80 to 100, thus proving the promise of the Kingsbury bearing.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Westinghouse Electric Company in Pittsburgh as a general engineer.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] He used this as an opportunity to advance the development of his thrust bearings in an industrial setting.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, the first test of his thrust bearing was a failure.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] His bearing overheated during the test and was discarded.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] This made the company skeptical of Kingsbury's invention, but Westinghouse's skepticism did not dent Kingsbury's enthusiasm.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would later fund his own test that proved his bearings successful.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, Westinghouse decided to stick to more conventional ball bearings for their motors.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tried to file for a U.S. patent during 1907.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] His initial application was rejected as a British patent had been granted in 1905 to A.G.M.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury was able to demonstrate that his 1898 test at the University of New Hampshire predated Michell's work, so in 1910 Kingsbury was awarded US patent No.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] 947242 for the tilting pad thrust bearing.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would eventually run his own business with the Westinghouse Machine Co. building his bearings.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] This allowed him to actively pursue applications for his newly patented thrust bearing.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] His first chance came when the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him the opportunity to demonstrate his bearing on their power generator at the Susquehanna River.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] His first bearing was a failure as it was immediately destroyed by Hillson wiping.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Fortunately for Kingsbury, the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him a second chance.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] His bearing succeeded this time, and worked flawlessly for the next 25 years.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] When it was inspected after 25 years, there was so little evidence of wear that it was calculated that the bearing would last 1,300 to 1,700 years.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] The same bearing is still operating smoothly today.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] In 1921, the Kingsbury thrust bearing had become so popular that Westinghouse could no longer keep up with the demand, thus prompting Kingsbury to set up his own manufacturing plant.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury continued to pursue his interest in bearings and tribology later in his life.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] One of his greatest achievements was his analysis of the effects of side leakage of lubricants from bearings.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] By recognizing the analogy in the equations for lubrication and those for electrical flow in a conductive fluid and variable depth, Kingsbury was able to make complicated predictions of slider load capacity well before the advent of computers.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury made important contributions to the area of boundary lubrication.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] He was the first to recognize that some fluid lubricants possess a friction-reducing property that is independent of viscosity, which he called 'oiliness'.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] His findings were of great significance since they demonstrated that the hydrodynamic theory of lubrication did not describe completely the lubricating mechanism of fluids.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Later work by Hardy and Doubleday showed that this property was related to the ability of polar lubricants to adsorb and form close-packed monolayers on the sliding surfaces.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] for his wide-ranging contributions to the field, Kingsbury was named as one of the 23 "Men of Tribology" by Duncan Dowson.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received many accolades for his contributions to science and engineering.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] He was awarded the Gold Medal of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in 1931; the Elliott Cresson Medal of the Franklin Institute; and honorary doctorates from the University of New Hampshire and Worcester Polytechnic Institute.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] He was elected Honorary Member of ASME in 1940.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] The Kingsbury Hall at the University of New Hampshire also pays homage to the great inventor.
[src:ambrose-swasey/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-davison-bailey] Bailey was born in what is now Salem Lakes, Wisconsin, son of Eugene M.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-davison-bailey] He obtained his BSc in Mechanical Engineering in 1903 from the Lewis Institute in Chicago, now Illinois Institute of Technology.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-davison-bailey] Before his graduation Bailey had started his career as draftsman at the U.S Wind Engine and Pump Company in Batavia, Illinois, and had been trouble man at the Evanston Heating Co. in Evanston, Illinois.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-davison-bailey] After his graduation Bailey started his lifelong career at the Chicago Edison Co., soon to be Commonwealth Edison.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-davison-bailey] From 1903 to 1905 he started as draftsman, from 1906 to 1916 he was assistant chief engineer at Fisk Street Station, and another chief engineer.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-davison-bailey] From 1921 to 1932 he was superintendent of generating stations of the company, and in 1933 appointed assistant chief operating engineer.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-davison-bailey] From 1936 to 1942 he was chief operating engineer and manager of the Super Power department.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-davison-bailey] The last years ten years at the company he was vice-president in charge of operations and engineering.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-davison-bailey] He retired on February 1, 1952 after 48 years of service.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-davison-bailey] In 1942 Bailey had been awarded the Honorary Doctor of Science by the Northwestern University.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-dow] Dow was born in Glasgow, Scotland as son of William Dow, a blacksmith, and Jean (Keppy) Dow in 1862.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-dow] He emigrated to the US in 1882 at the age of twenty.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-dow] In 1893 Dow was appointed the first plant manager of the first municipally owned power plant in Detroit, and electrical engineer for the city of Detroit.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-dow] The power plant had been built as a result of Hazen Pingree's efforts to break the power of corporations over Detroit City politics.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-dow] It was during this time that Henry Ford worked under Dow at one of the Detroit Edison substations.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-dow] Dow took Ford with him to the 1896 annual convention of the Association of Edison Illuminating Companies being held that year in New York City.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-dow] It was at this convention that Dow introduced Ford to Thomas Edison, the meeting with, and encouragement from, the great scientist becoming a great inspiration to Ford in completing his first car.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-dow] Dow was appointed water commissioner for the city of Detroit in 1916-1921 and again in 1925-1932.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-dow] In 1932, he was made the president of Detroit Edison and served until 1940.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-dow] He was elected president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers for the 1928-1929 year.
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-dow] He was a member of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, American Society of Civil Engineers, American Institute of Electrical Engineers, Institute of Electrical Engineers (Great Britain), Institute of Mechanical Engineers (Great Britain).
[src:ambrose-swasey/alex-dow] Dow also served as the President of The Engineering Society of Detroit from 1900-1901.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] Swasey was born near Exeter, New Hampshire to Nathaniel and Abigail Swasey.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] He apprenticed as a machinist at the Exeter Machine Works and was afterwards employed at Pratt & Whitney.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] As his career progressed, he became a foreman in the gear-cutting section.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] He developed a new technique for making gear-tooth cutters.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] In 1880, he and Warner formed their eponymous firm, which quickly moved to Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] Swasey would perform the engineering and machine development at this company.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] The close friends Warner and Swasey built their homes next to each other on Euclid Avenue in Cleveland, a street that was known as "Millionaire's Row".
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] In addition to army ordnance contracts, the firm of Warner & Swasey became notable for their work on astronomical observatories and equipment.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] The founders were interested in astronomy as an avocation, and in the field's quest for better optical telescopes, which was burgeoning at the time.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] They also realized that obtaining contracts to build large astronomical observatories would provide publicity for their company.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] In 1885, Swasey completed work at McCormick Observatory on the 45-foot dome, which was the largest in the world, and had a unique, 3 shutter design.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] In 1887, Swasey built the mount for the 36-inch refracting telescope at Lick Observatory.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] In 1898, he manufactured a dividing engine for the U.S.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] Naval Observatory that was used to make the meridian circles.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] Both the building and dome of the Dominion Astrophysical Observatory were made by Warner and Swasey Co.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] Other observatory telescopes and components were built by the company at the Kenwood Observatory, Yerkes Observatory, Argentine National Observatory, the Swasey Observatory at Denison University, and the Case School of Applied Science Observatory.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] From 1904 until 1905, he was the president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] Both Warner and Swasey were amateur astronomers.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] When they became trustees of the Case School of Applied Science, they donated to the school their private observatory, which they had built between their neighboring houses in East Cleveland.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] Relocated to a new building, this became the Warner and Swasey Observatory.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] The observatory maintained by the department today is still known by this name today.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] Swasey Hall (1917, "懷士堂"), a red brick hall, is the landmark of Sun Yat-sen University, one of the top colleges in China.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] It was named after Swasey for his USD$25000 donation to the then university Christian YMCA society hall.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] The chimes in the chapel were included as a memorial to his wife, Lavinia Marston Swasey.
[src:ambrose-swasey/ambrose-swasey] The Warner & Swasey Company he cofounded would continue until 1980, when it was acquired by Bendix Corporation.
[src:ambrose-swasey/asme-medal] The **ASME Medal**, created in 1920, is the highest award bestowed by the ASME (founded as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers) Board of Governors for "eminently distinguished engineering achievement".
[src:ambrose-swasey/asme-medal] The award has been presented every year since 1996 (first medalist was awarded in 1921), and it consists of a $15,000 honorarium, a certificate, a travel supplement not to exceed $750, and a gold medal inscribed with the words, "What is not yet, may be".
[src:ambrose-swasey/asme-medal] ASME also gives out a number of other awards yearly, including the Edwin F.
[src:ambrose-swasey/asme-medal] Church Medal, the Holley medal, and the Soichiro Honda medal.
